Downloaded provided files (training and tesing datasets). Then I load them.

trainingS = read.csv("pml-training.csv", na.strings=c("", "NA", "NULL"))
testingS = read.csv("pml-testing.csv", na.strings=c("", "NA", "NULL"))
  1. Cleaning data:
  1. Remove variables with too many NA’s (mostly blank)
  2. Remove all other unrelevant variables and user name, timestamps and window.
#a
trainingC <- trainingS[ , colSums(is.na(trainingS)) == 0]
#dim(trainingC) [1] 19622 60
#b
remove = c('X', 'user_name', 'raw_timestamp_part_1', 'raw_timestamp_part_2', 'cvtd_timestamp', 'new_window', 'num_window')
trainingCl <- trainingC[, -which(names(trainingC) %in% remove)]
#dim(trainingCl) [1] 19622 53

c)Use nearZeroVar() from caret to detect vars that have low variance d)Use findCorrelation to pinpoint and remove varibales with high correlation and remove them.

#c
zvar= nearZeroVar(trainingCl[sapply(trainingCl, is.numeric)], saveMetrics = TRUE)
trainingZvar = trainingCl[,zvar[, 'nzv']==0]
#dim(trainingZvar) [1]19622 53

#d
corrT <-cor(na.omit(trainingZvar[sapply(trainingZvar, is.numeric)]))
# dim(corrT) [1] 52 52
remC = findCorrelation(corrT, cutoff = .90, verbose = TRUE)
trainingClean = trainingZvar[,-remC]
dim(trainingClean)

Ok then we are set to split for training and testing (19622 samples and 46 vars) Training set: 14718 samples Testing set: 4904

index <- createDataPartition(y=trainingClean$classe, p=0.7, list=FALSE)
training <- trainingClean[index,]
testing <- trainingClean[-index,]
dim(training)
## [1] 13737    46
dim(testing)
## [1] 5885   46
  1. Ready to perform the analysis:
  1. Rpart model classification tree
  2. Error rate of rpart model on the testing data (0.58).Poor result, better check something else!!

modelRp <- train(classe ~ .,method="rpart",data=training)

#b)
predRp<-predict(modelRp,testing)
pm<- with(testing,table(predRp,classe))
errorRate <- sum(diag(pm))/sum(as.vector(pm))
errorRate
## [1] 0.498

Random forest will use many trees and find how to reduce the variance: a)Random forest fitting (estimate error rate: OOB 0.76%, now see with testing ). c) Error rate Random Forest check with testing data: 0.994. Very accurate!

#b)
set.seed(12345)

pml_write_files = function(x){
  n = length(x)
  for(i in 1:n){
    filename = paste0("problem_id_",i,".txt")
    write.table(x[i],file=filename,quote=FALSE,row.names=FALSE,col.names=FALSE)
  }
}
